FL,306,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30505
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F305A1784132319
OL,3,CWill it rain for the start of the
OL,4,Cschool holidays?
OL,6,FFor the time being the weather looks
OL,7,Fsettled and dry - with more manageable
OL,8,Fheat compared to the heatwaves in June
OL,9,Fand May.
OL,11,FThe temperatures now are not quite as
OL,12,Fhigh, as summer continues to drift to
OL,13,Fthe mid way point.
OL,15,FThe only glitches will be some early
OL,16,Fcloud - more so around north-east
OL,17,Fcoasts - and some inland cloud with
OL,18,Fmist and fog before giving way as the
OL,19,Fsun gets to work through the morning.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G5/6
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,306,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30506
SC,0006
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F305A1784132319
OL,3,CWill it rain for the start of the
OL,4,Cschool holidays?
OL,6,FSo far, the UK as seen higher than
OL,7,Faverage amounts of sunshine this
OL,8,Fsummer - while Scotland, where we also
OL,9,Fsee the longest amount of daylight at
OL,10,Fthis time of year, is currently at its
OL,11,Faverage.
OL,13,FWith high sunshine hours, as far back
OL,14,Fas May, solar power has been higher
OL,15,Fthan usual - this follows a record
OL,16,Fbreaking year for solar power last
OL,17,Fyear.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G6/6
